properties.Title: High Water Advisory Alert Issued For The Interlake
properties.Summary:
Description: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a High Water Advisory for parts of the Interlake region due to expected high flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up to date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.

Area: Interlake region of Manitoba

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant prolonged rainfall is expected. Total rainfall: 60 to 100 mm. Locations: From Natuashish to Hopedale. Timespan: Beginning near noon Friday and tapering off to showers Sunday afternoon. Remarks: Rainfall amounts could exceed warning criteria of 75 mm in 48 hours. It is also likely that some snow will accumulate over the highest elevations of the inland terrain. Anyone using mountain trails should be prepared for winter weather. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A prolonged period of significant coastal rain and high-elevation snow is expected. Total rainfall: 30 to 50 mm near Nain and 60 to 90 mm near Natuashish. Total snowfall: 10 to 20 cm inland and over higher terrain. Timespan: this morning until Sunday afternoon. Remarks: Rain, at times heavy, is expected along the north coast of Labrador today through Sunday. Over the higher elevations inland, precipitation will fall as heavy accumulating snow until midday Saturday before changing to a mixture of rain and wet snow. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Be prepared for possible winter conditions at higher elevations. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with gusty winds and visibility frequently near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. An area of high pressure situated over the Arctic Ocean and an intense low pressure system over the Gulf of Alaska will continue to produce conditions favourable for strong, gusty winds near the Richardson Mountains. The strong winds, falling snow and existing snow pack will combine to produce blizzard conditions through at least Friday. ### Travel is expected to be extremely hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 4 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-18T15:48:19-00:00

Area: Dempster

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A short period of significant rainfall is expected. Total rainfall: localized areas of 20 to 30 mm in heavy downpours. Locations: eastern and southern Avalon Peninsula. Timespan: early this morning until midday today. Remarks: Rain will spread northward across the Avalon Peninsula early this morning with a risk of thundershowers over southern parts of the peninsula. properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. A low pressure system tracking northeastwards out of the northern Prairie provinces will spread snow into Whale Cove, Rankin Inlet, and Chesterfield Inlet on Friday. The snow may be mixed at times with rain, which may limit accumulations initially, before precipitation intensifies Friday night into Saturday. Total accumulations will likely be in the 10 to 15 cm range by the time the snow tapers off on Sunday. This snowfall warning may be expanded to Naujaat later today for heavy snowfall expected on Saturday into Sunday. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-19T00:12:44-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-18T08:13:44-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.1324037704.2019
Area: Rankin Region including Whale Cove, Chesterfield Inlet
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. Maximum gusts: 80 km/h, except locally 100 in areas prone to enhanced easterlies. Locations: western Newfoundland. Timespan: continuing until early Friday morning. Remarks: Local enhancement in easterly flow typically occurs in the vicinities of Cape St. George, Port au Port Bay, the outer Bay of Islands, Trout River Bay, Bonne Bay, Western Brook Pond and St. Pauls Bay. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. Wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
